{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504436"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:16:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:16:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2333"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2333"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.02,0.01,0.55,0.31]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2333"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111538"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2333"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2333"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93625"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1914"},{"type":"tags","id":"3051"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1154"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1155"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45408"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111538"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with confusion, jaundice and abdominal distension developing over several days. His wife reports deteriorating sleep and concentration, noting this is \u0022unlike his usual drunk self\u0022. He has a history of alcohol use disorder, consuming 8-10 standard drinks daily for many years. He has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 12/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.6\u00b0C. He is visibly jaundiced with conjunctival icterus, palmar erythema and spider naevi across his chest and arms. His abdomen is grossly distended with shifting dullness. His Glasgow Coma Scale score is 10/15. Cardiorespiratory examination is unremarkable. Blood samples are collected for laboratory analysis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urgent computed tomography of the abdomen","Serum alpha fetoprotein level","Mini-mental State Examination","Diagnostic paracentesis with microscopy and culture","Serum ammonia level"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of decompensated liver cirrhosis including jaundice, ascites, and confusion. While hepatic encephalopathy might seem likely given his chronic alcohol use, the presence of fever (38.6\u00b0C) with acute onset confusion should prompt investigation for infection first, particularly spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP). SBP is a life-threatening condition that occurs in 10-30% of cirrhotic patients with ascites.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagnostic paracentesis with microscopy and culture\u003C/strong\u003E is the essential first investigation. A neutrophil count \u0026gt;250 cells/mm\u00b3 in the ascitic fluid confirms SBP and should prompt immediate antibiotic therapy. The mortality rate of untreated SBP approaches 50%, making this the priority investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum ammonia level\u003C/strong\u003E might help confirm hepatic encephalopathy, but would not explain the fever. Additionally, ammonia levels correlate poorly with encephalopathy severity and are not routinely recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMini-mental State Examination\u003C/strong\u003E would not help differentiate between encephalopathy and infection-related confusion, and the patient\u0027s low GCS would make this difficult to perform.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent computed tomography of the abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E might show cirrhotic changes but would not diagnose or exclude SBP. While it might reveal other pathology, it should not delay paracentesis in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum alpha fetoprotein level\u003C/strong\u003E is used to screen for hepatocellular carcinoma in cirrhotic patients but is not relevant to the acute presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of fever, confusion, and ascites in a cirrhotic patient should always trigger consideration of SBP. Even if hepatic encephalopathy is present, infection is a common precipitant and must be excluded first.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis should always be considered in patients with cirrhosis who suddenly deteriorate.","Fever with new onset confusion in a cirrhotic patient should prompt investigation for infection before attributing symptoms to hepatic encephalopathy.","Diagnostic paracentesis should be performed in all patients with cirrhosis and ascites admitted to hospital."],"references":["Mattos AA, Wiltgen D, Jotz RF, et al. Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis and extraperitoneal infections in patients with cirrhosis. Ann Hepatol 2020; 19:451.","Tit\u00f3 L, Rimola A, Gin\u00e8s P, et al. Recurrence of spontaneous bacterial peritonitis in cirrhosis: frequency and predictive factors. Hepatology 1988; 8:27.","Akriviadis EA, Runyon BA. Utility of an algorithm in differentiating spontaneous from secondary bacterial peritonitis. Gastroenterology 1990; 98:127."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93625"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2333"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93625"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-16T09:23:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-16T09:24:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2333"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111538"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data